{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01GWA5VXEdwrFHFFuSBD31Sg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The develop workflow is a container workflow. It doesn't directly consume CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT. The CLOCHE_TASK_ID would just be an env var in the container.\n\nThe problem is that prepare-prompt outputs plain text, so I can't use `output.CLOCHE_TASK_ID` on the wire. \n\nOptions:\n1. Make prepare-prompt output JSON instead\n2. Have prepare-prompt pass CLOCHE_TASK_ID through to its own output somehow\n3. Just pass it directly - don't wire from prepare-prompt, wire from ready-tasks but that's not how the graph works (ready-tasks doesn't connect to develop)\n\n\n4. Change prepare-prompt to output JSON with both the task ID and prompt content, then use output mappings in the develop step to extract CLOCHE_TASK_ID as an env var for the container workflow.\n\nI need to verify how the host executor handles env vars from output mappings when triggering a workflow_name step. So the prepare-prompt script writes its output to the CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT environment variable, which the host executor then passes along to the develop step. That means the prompt gets injected into the container workflow somehow, even though the implement step reads from a static file path - there must be some mechanism that writes the injected prompt to that file location before the container runs.\n\nThe simplest solution is to have prepare-prompt output JSON containing both the prompt and the task ID, so the develop wire can extract the task ID from that structured output rather than trying to pass it as a separate environment variable.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1100,"cache_read_input_tokens":23414,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1100},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_avail